  "texts": [
    "Now, noticing that we can rewritesign ′ ϵ (f)f ∂ w f = ∂ w (sign ϵ (f)f -|f | ϵ), sign ′ ϵ (f)f ∂ A f = ∂ A (sign ϵ (f)f -|f | ϵ),we can integrate back by parts the three terms containing these factors (with respect to A the first one, with respect to w the other two) and take the limit ϵ → 0, to prove that they all vanish.",
    "Since the second to last term is nonpositive for any ε, we thus conclude that the L1 (R × I) norm of f (t, A, w) is non-increasing, namely d dt ∫ R×I |f |(t, A, w)dAdw ≤ 0.Introducing now the negative part f - ϵ (t, A, w) of the solution via the same regularization asf - ϵ (t, A, w) = 1 2 (|f | ϵ (t, A, w) -f (t, A, w)),we exploit the fact that all operators on the right-hand side of equation ( 64) are mass-preserving to infer that d dt∫ R×I f - ϵ (t, A, w)dAdw = 1 2 d dt ∫ R×I |f | ϵ (t, A, w)dAdw - 1 2 d dt ∫ R×I f (t, A, w)dAdw = 1 2 d dt ∫ R×I |f | ϵ (t, A, w)dAdw,and that in the limit ϵ → 0 it holds d dt ∫ R×I f -(t, A, w)dAdw ≤ 0, for all t > 0, concluding that the solution f (t, A, w) remains indeed nonnegative.",
    "□ Remark 7.",
    "From Proposition 6 it follows that the L 1 (R × I) regularity of the initial datum is preserved, since the model is mass-preserving.",
    "Note that we cannot expect more than L 1 regularity, because the transport operator along the activity leads to the formation of a Dirac delta in the limit t → +∞.Proposition 7."
  ],
